solutions.content:
# Intuition
My first thought was to apply Floyd-Warshall's algorithm but adding a edge to graph and doing relaxation for newly inserted edge will take $$O(n^2)$$. If we look at contraints they are not that strict we can easily apply dijstra's algorithm for each query to get distance between nodes and adding a edge to graph also won't effect much for individual distance calculation.

# Approach
We can build an adjacency list, building adjacency list will take $$O(E)$$ and adding a edge to adjacency list will take $O(1)$ time complexity.

From here we can apply dijkstra algorithm for each query (node1, node2) for the complexity of $O(V \cdot log(E + V))$.

## Dijstras
Following is the steps for dijstra's algorithm that finds distance of all the nodes from node `from`.

- We keep distance array to keep track of minimum distance from `from` node to every other node (initially all to `INT_MAX`). We also need visited boolean array which has the nodes marked `true` if minimum distance to that node is already found.
- Min Priority queue is used to find the next node that is closest to `from` node and has not been visited.
- Distance of `from` to `from` is initialised to 0 and pushed to priority queue to start the algorithm.
- Now we pick the top most `node` at priority queue and go to it's neighbour and check if we can perform any edge relaxation from the neighbour nodes of this `node` if there is edge relaxation performed we add that relaxation to priority queue as contender for next better pick.
- At the end distance array will have minimum distance from node `from` to all the other nodes.


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
    - Build: $O(E)$
    - Add Edge: $O(1)$
    - Shortest Path: $O(V \cdot log(E + V))$
- Space complexity:
    - Graph will take $O(E + V)$
    - Dijstra algorithm takes $OD(E + V)$


