# Complexity
- Time complexity of shortestPath(): O(E*logV) - time complexity of Dijkstra algorithm, we have logV due to minHeap, and E since in worst case we will have to traverse all edges before we reach destination. 

Why it's logV instead of logE: O(E*logE) -> O(E*log(V^2)) [we can move exponent outside of logarithm] -> O(E*2*logV) -> O(E*logV) [we can remove constants in Big-O notation]

---

- Overall Space complexity: O(V + E) V for visited array, V + E for adjList

# Code
```
class Graph {
    private Map<Integer, List<int[]>> adjList = new HashMap<>(); // from - list of pairs<to, wei>
    private final int n; // n is immutable since new edges(from, to) within [0, n-1]

    public Graph(int n, int[][] edges) {
        this.n = n;
        for(var edge: edges) addEdge(edge);
    }

    public void addEdge(int[] edge) {
        adjList.computeIfAbsent(edge[0], k -> new ArrayList<>())
                .add(new int[]{edge[1], edge[2]});
    }

    // Dijkstra alg(BFS with MinHeap): 1) Add src to queue, 
    // 2) Pop pair(node, wei) with lowest weight, check if it's dest or visited, otherwise visit node, 
    // 3) Add all outgoing edges(with weights) from popped node to MinHeap
    // NB: if queue.isEmpty & dest not found -> it can't be reached from src, return -1
    public int shortestPath(int src, int dest) {
        var queue = new PriorityQueue<int[]>((a, b) -> a[1] - b[1]);
        var visited = new boolean[n];
        queue.add(new int[]{src, 0}); // wei=0 since we start from src

        while(!queue.isEmpty()) {
            var nodeWei = queue.poll();
            int node = nodeWei[0], wei = nodeWei[1];

            if(visited[node]) continue;
            if(node == dest) return wei;

            visited[node] = true;

            adjList.getOrDefault(node, Collections.emptyList())
                .forEach(e -> queue.add(new int[]{e[0], wei + e[1]}));
        }

        return -1;
    }
}
```

