solutions.content:
This problem requires a shortest path with an ever changing graph, so, among all the possible options, we might go for a Dijkstra that should work well, given the relatively low constraints we will face.

We will start declaring `maxNodes` with a value of `100` (as per specs), then at instance level:
* `connections`, an array of `maxNodes` vectors of pairs we will use later to track the information of each edge;
* `costs` is an array of `maxNodes` cells we will use in our traversal.

In the constructor we will take each `edge` in `edges` and:
* create a pair with destination (ie: `edge[1]`) and cost (ie: `edge[2]`);
* push said pair in the vector matching the origin (`edge[0]`) in `connection`.

In `addEdge` we will do the same for the provided `edge`.

The `shortestPath` function might carry more complexity, by:
* declare `res` and assign the result of calling `minPath` with `n1` and `n2`;
* `return` `-1` if `res == INT_MAX` or `res` otherwise.

`minPath` will take two nodes `start` and `dest` and:
* `return` `0` if `start` and `end` match;
* declare `pq` as a min heap of vectors;
* fill `costs` with `INT_MAX`;
* set `costs[start]` to `0` (we start from there, so no cost);
* take each `connection` we can get from `start` (ie: `connections[start]`) and:
    * extract `to` and `cost` from it;
    * push a vector with `{cost, to, start}` in `pq`;
* looping with a nice optimised Dijkstra loop that will run `while` `pq` is not empty and will:
    * take the top of `pq` and store it in `top`;
    * extract `cost`, `currNode` and `prevNode` from it;
    * pop the top out of `pq`;
    * `continue` if we have already been here (ie: `costs[currNode] != INT_MAX`, since it will never be the case with a node we visited in this run);
    * update `costs[currNode]` to the be `cost` (since we know that the first time we reach each node also has to be the cheapest);
    * `break` if we reached `dest`;
    * if not, for each `connection` we can get from `currNode` (ie: `connections[currNode]`) we will:
    * extract `to` and `cost` from it;
    * push a vector with `{costs[currNode] + cost, to, currNode}` in `pq`;
* finally, `return` `costs[dest]`. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(e)$$ (constructor and `shortestPath`), $$O(1)$$ (`addEdge`)
- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$

# Code
```cpp
constexpr int maxNodes = 100;

class Graph {
    vector<pair<int, int>> connections[maxNodes];
    int costs[maxNodes];
    int minPath(int start, int dest) {
        // edge case
        if (start == dest) return 0;
        // support variables
        priority_queue<vector<int>, vector<vector<int>>, greater<vector<int>>> pq;
        // preparing costs and pq;
        fill(costs, costs + maxNodes, INT_MAX);
        costs[start] = 0;
        for (auto &connection: connections[start]) {
            auto [to, cost] = connection;
            pq.push({cost, to, start});
        }
        // Dijkstra!
        while (pq.size()) {
            // popping the top of pq
            auto &top = pq.top();
            int cost = top[0], currNode = top[1], prevNode = top[2];
            pq.pop();
            // already been here
            if (costs[currNode] != INT_MAX) continue;
            costs[currNode] = cost;
            if (currNode == dest) break;
            for (auto &connection: connections[currNode]) {
                auto [to, cost] = connection;
                pq.push({costs[currNode] + cost, to, currNode});
            }
        }
        return costs[dest];
    }
public:
    Graph(int n, vector<vector<int>> &edges) {
        for (auto &edge: edges) connections[edge[0]].push_back({edge[1], edge[2]});
    }

    void addEdge(vector<int> edge) {
        connections[edge[0]].push_back({edge[1], edge[2]});
    }

    int shortestPath(int n1, int n2) {
        int res = minPath(n1, n2);
        return res == INT_MAX ? -1 : res;
    }
};
