# Intuition
The graph is clearly Directed + Weighted, and problem demands shortest paths between 2 nodes. Hence, Dijkstra's is the simplest approach to run each time ```int shortestPath(int node1, int node2)``` is executed.

# Approach
1. To traverse any graph (BFS or DFS or DIJKSTRA), we need an aadjacency list. This lets you look up a node's neighbors in ```O(1)``` Time while using ```(V * E)``` Space. From there we add each edge to this data structure.

2. Dijsktra's Shortest path requires you to maintain the shortest distance found for all N nodes. We also need a PriorityQueue i.e Min Heap to organize the nodes being traversed. This PriorityQueue holds nodes represented by a. nodeID and b. distance traveled to reach this node so far. The Heap will prioritize the nodes with the LEAST distance traveled.
3. For each node popped from the heap, explore the neighbors pulled from the adjacency list. Each neighbor/child node will have its cost added to the popped node's distance traveled. If the total is an improvement on the child's min distance, update it and enqueue it into the Heap.
4. Eventually all reachable nodes will have their min distance optimized to the abosulte best, and the heap has nothing to be enqueued (i.e. empty). Remember that the starting node may not be able to reach the target node.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
```O(E * log|V|) ``` since the Heap takes ```log(v)``` to pop the next node each time. This is multiplied by ```(E + V)``` because we are traversing all neighboring nodes (i.e. number of edges). This does not TLE only because the number of times ```int shortestPath(int node1, int node2)``` is executed is at most 100x.

- Space complexity:
```(V * E)``` to store adjacency list.

If something in this seems incorrect, feel free to comment.

# Code
```
class Graph {

    List<Pair<Integer, Integer>>[] adjList;
    int n;
    public Graph(int n, int[][] edges) {
        produceAdjList(n, edges);
    }

    private void produceAdjList(int n, int[][] edges) {
        // Initialize adjacency list with empty neighbors per node.
        this.n = n;
        this.adjList = new ArrayList[n];

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
            adjList[i] = new ArrayList();

        // Populate adjacency list with each edge.
        for (int[] edge : edges)
            addEdge(edge);
    }

    public void addEdge(int[] edge) {
        // For FROM, add connection with TO + COST.
        int from = edge[0], to = edge[1], cost = edge[2];
        adjList[from].add(new Pair(to, cost));
    }

    public int shortestPath(int node1, int node2) {
        // Maintain shortest path found per node.
        int[] minDist = new int[n];
        Arrays.fill(minDist, Integer.MAX_VALUE);

        // Begin with starting node having min distance 0.
        minDist[node1] = 0;

        // PriorityQueue sorts nodes by those traveling smallest distance.
        // Each Pair is represented as [nodeId, distanceTraveled].
        PriorityQueue<Pair<Integer, Integer>> pq = new PriorityQueue<>((a, b) -> a.getValue() - b.getValue());

        // Enque first node with 0 distance.
        pq.add(new Pair(node1, 0));

        // Execute Dijkstra's Shortest path.
        while (!pq.isEmpty()) {
            // Get next node.
            Pair<Integer, Integer> entry = pq.poll();
            int node = entry.getKey();
            int dist = entry.getValue();

            // Go thru neighbors to continue search.
            for (var child : adjList[node]) {
                // Check if distance is improved.
                int childDist = child.getValue() + dist;
                int childNode = child.getKey();
                if (childDist < minDist[childNode]) {
                    // Mark new shortest distance and enqeue node.
                    minDist[childNode] = childDist;
                    pq.add(new Pair(childNode, childDist));
                }
            }
        }

        // Send result if we ever found the target.
        return minDist[node2] == Integer.MAX_VALUE ? -1 : minDist[node2];
    }
}
```

