# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We need to find the shortest path between two nodes in a graph. To do that, we can use an algorithm called Dijkstra's algorithm.


# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

We will create an adjacency list to represent the graph.
We will initialize the distance of all nodes to infinity, except the starting node which is 0.

We will use a priority queue to store the nodes that we need to process next. We will insert the starting node with distance 0 into the priority queue.

We will then process the nodes in the priority queue until we reach the destination node or the priority queue is empty.

For each node we process, we will look at its neighbors and update their distances if the path through the current node is shorter than their current distances.

After processing all the neighbors of a node, we will insert them into the priority queue.

We will repeat steps 4-6 until we reach the destination node or the priority queue is empty.

Finally, we will return the shortest distance to the destination node

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Time complexity: O(ElogV) where E is the number of edges and V is the number of vertices in the graph. This is because we process each edge once and insert each node into the priority queue once. The time complexity can be reduced to O(E+VlogV) using a Fibonacci heap.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Space complexity: O(V) for the distance array and O(V) for the priority queue. Therefore, the space complexity is O(V).
