# Intuition
For initializing graph, we first need to add edges from edges[i][0] to edges[i][1] with edge weight as edges[i][2].To find shortest distance between two nodes, we need to use Djikstra's algorithm. 
**Note**: Here the source node is node1 and not 0, so take care while solving the algorithm.

# Approach
1. With the given "n" and edges array, we create graph using adjacency list and add all the edges with edge-weight to create directed graph. This is done in constructor which is called while creating object of the class.
2. For addEdge, we add extra edge from edge[0] to edge[1] with edge-weight as edge[2].
3. To find shortest distance, we use Djikstra's algorithm.
4. For this,we use PriorityQueue(min-heap) so that we get minimum distance required to reach the destination node.
5. We initialize distance array with infinite distance and keep on updating it whenever shorter distance to that path is discovered.
6. If we cannot reach destination node, distance will be infinite and we will return -1. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O((N+E)*logN). Going through N nodes and E edges and log N for priority queue

- Space complexity:
O(N). Distance array and priority queue

# Code
```
//it is used to create graph
//where adjacent= neighbouring node to the current node
//edgecost=cost required to reach that node
class Node{
    int adjacent,edgeCost;
    Node(int adjacent,int edgeCost){
        this.adjacent=adjacent;
        this.edgeCost=edgeCost;
    }
}

//it is stored in queue to represent node with it's current distance
class Pair{
    int node,distance;
    Pair(int node,int distance){
        this.node=node;
        this.distance=distance;
    }
}

class Graph {
    //adjacency list for graph
    ArrayList<ArrayList<Node>> adj=new ArrayList<>();

    public Graph(int n, int[][] edges) {
        //adding empty array for all "n" nodes
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            ArrayList<Node> arr=new ArrayList<>();
            adj.add(arr);
        }
        //creating edges between two nodes with given edge weight
        for(int i=0;i<edges.length;i++){
            adj.get(edges[i][0]).add(new Node(edges[i][1],edges[i][2]));
        }
    }

    //creating edges between two nodes with given edge weight
    public void addEdge(int[] edges) {
        adj.get(edges[0]).add(new Node(edges[1],edges[2]));
    }

    public int shortestPath(int node1, int node2) {
        //min-heap to store node with minimum path distance
        PriorityQueue<Pair> pq=new PriorityQueue<Pair>((x,y)-> x.distance-y.distance);
        pq.offer(new Pair(node1,0));
        int[] dist=new int[adj.size()];
        //declaring distance array with all values intially as infinity
        for(int i=0;i<dist.length;i++){
            dist[i]=(int)(1e9);
        }
        //source node distance is assigned to 0
        dist[node1]=0;
        while(pq.size()!=0){
            //removing pair from queue
            Pair p=pq.poll();
            int distance=p.distance;
            int node=p.node;
            //traversing neighbouring nodes 
            for(int i=0;i<adj.get(node).size();i++){
                int adjacent=adj.get(node).get(i).adjacent;
                int edgeCost=adj.get(node).get(i).edgeCost;
                //if computed path distance is smaller,update it
                if(distance+edgeCost<dist[adjacent]){
                    dist[adjacent]=distance+edgeCost;
                    pq.add(new Pair(adjacent,dist[adjacent]));
                }
            }
        }
        //if distance of destination node is infinity,it can be reached and return -1
        //else return the distance
        return dist[node2]==(int)(1e9)?-1:dist[node2];
