solutions.content:
Brute forcing our way out of this problem might seem tempting, but it is not very rewarding and I am a firm believe that as an engineer one should always at least *try* to do better.

And better we can do, if we notice that if we know that the range `[1, n]` has `x == n / 3` multiples of, say, `3`, then we know that they will all be in the range `[3, x]`, creating a summation like `3 + 6 + 9 + ... + (x - 1) * 3 + x * 3`, or, in other words: `(1 + 2 + 3 + ... + (x - 1) + x) * 3`.

But, hey, we know how to compute that, with Gauss' formula for summations from `1` to `x`: `(x + 1) * x / 2`.

So, we can initially try to solve our problem `return`ing the sum of:
* all the multiples of `3` up to `n`: `gauss(n / 3) * 3`;
* all the multiples of `5` up to `n`: `gauss(n / 5) * 5`;
* all the multiples of `7` up to `n`: `gauss(n / 7) * 7`.

As easy as that? Not really, because now we are counting twice all the multiples of any two among `3`, `5` or `7`.

We can easily fix that, subtracting the summation of all the numbers matching this criteria, so we will reduce our result by:
* all the multiples of `3 * 5` up to `n`: `gauss(n / 15) * 15`;
* all the multiples of `3 * 7` up to `n`: `gauss(n / 21) * 21`;
* all the multiples of `5 * 7` up to `n`: `gauss(n / 35) * 35`.

Done?

Almost, one last little adjustement: now we are removing twice all the multiples of `3`, `5` and `7`, so we will just have to add:
* all the multiples of `3 * 5 * 7` up to `n`: `gauss(n / 105) * 105`.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(1)$$
- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$

# Code
```cpp
class Solution {
    int gauss(int x) {
        return (x + 1) * x >> 1;
    }
public:
    int sumOfMultiples(int n) {
        return gauss(n / 3) * 3 + gauss(n / 5) * 5 + gauss(n / 7) * 7
            - gauss(n / 15) * 15 - gauss(n / 21) * 21 - gauss(n / 35) * 35
            + gauss(n / 105) * 105;
    }
};
```

Micro-optimisation of the same logic, computing only when necessary:

```cpp
class Solution {
    int gauss(int x) {
        return (x + 1) * x >> 1;
    }
public:
    int sumOfMultiples(int n) {
        // support variables
        int res = gauss(n / 3) * 3 + gauss(n / 5) * 5 + gauss(n / 7) * 7;
        // discounting multiples of two factors
        if (n > 14) res -= gauss(n / 15) * 15 + gauss(n / 21) * 21 + gauss(n / 35) * 35;
        // adjusting for multiples of all 3
        if (n > 104) res += gauss(n / 105) * 105;
        return res;
    }
};
