# Intuition
So as we already know this is the basic function of java script. My thoughts about the code are as follows:
Here,createHelloWorld is a function that returns another function. The inner function takes no arguments and simply returns the string "Hello World".

When createHelloWorld is called, it creates a new execution context with its own variable environment. When the inner function is returned, it retains a reference to the variable environment of the outer function, creating a closure.

The closure allows the returned function to access variables defined in the outer function, even after the outer function has finished executing. In this case, the inner function does not access any variables from the outer function, but the closure is still created and demonstrates how closures work.

To use the returned function, createHelloWorld is called and the result is assigned to the variable f. f is then called as a function with the syntax f(), which executes the inner function and returns the string "Hello World".

