solutions.content:
Rather trivial problem, we will solve it the first time with just a loop.

After declaring our usual result variable `res` as an empty array, we will loop with `i` from `0` up to the length `len` of `arr` and:
* create a new slice of `arr` from `i` to `i + k`;
* insert it in `res`;
* increase `i` by `k`.

Once done, we can `return` `res`.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$

# Code
```ts
const chunk = (arr: any[], k: number): any[][] => {
    // support variables
    const res = [];
    // parsing arr
    for (let i = 0, len = arr.length; i < len;) res.push(arr.slice(i, i += k));
    return res;
};
```

Same logic, a bit hackier to keep it as a one-liner:
* we will use the trick of adding one extra parameter not to have to declare an extra variable on a separate line, so `i` will be there, defaulted to `0`;
* thanks to `Array.from()` we can create a "fictitious" object with only a property, `length`, that will be equal to the amount of chunks we need to create (the ceiling of the division of the number of elements in `arr`, divided by `k`), to iterate through it;
* `Array.from()` also take a second parameter that is an optional mapping function - we will use it to create chunks similar to the logic used in the above solution and directly `return` that.

```ts
const chunk = (arr: any[], k: number, i: number = 0): any[][] => {
    return Array.from({length: Math.ceil(arr.length / k)}, () => arr.slice(i, i += k));
};
```

