# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
There are two arguments, one is the array and two is the size. When size is fixed, we can solve it with a single loop.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Run through the array and when the (index + 1) is multiple of 'size', create a new chunk and push it to the main array. Few edge cases are covered with conditionals.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$ as only one loop and push is of $$O(1)$$.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$ since we have used two one dimensional array only. Out of that the chunk array is of fixed size. Hence, $$O(n + k) = O(n)$$, where k is constant.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
/**
 * @param {Array} arr
 * @param {number} size
 * @return {Array}
 */
var chunk = function(arr, size) {
    let outputArr = [];
    let chunkArr = [];
    if(arr.length < 1){
        return [];
    }
    if (size > arr.length){
        outputArr = [arr];
        return outputArr;
    }
	for(let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++){
        if (size === 1){
            outputArr.push([arr[i]]);
        } else {
            chunkArr.push(arr[i]);
            if (((i+1) % size) == 0){
                outputArr.push([...chunkArr]);
                chunkArr = [];
            } else if (arr.length - 1 === i){
                outputArr.push(chunkArr);
            }
        }
    }
    return outputArr;
};

```

