# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We can use Splice Array method to solve this as it's one of the many other solutions.
As per the test cases, we can break the cases as you can see in the below code.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We can divide the input array length with the given size to get a quotient where it denotes the possible number of chunks. For example, if quotient is 2 then chunks are 2. If quotient is 2.something (a decimal value like 2.3333) then possiblee number of chunks would be 3 (ceil of 2.something) 

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
/**
 * @param {Array} arr
 * @param {number} size
 * @return {Array[]}
 */

var chunk = function(arr, size) {
    let outputArray = [];

    if (arr.length !== 0) {
        if (arr.length < size) {
            outputArray = [arr];
        } else {
            const quotient = arr.length / size;
            let splicedArray = [...arr];
            for (let i=0; i<quotient; i++) {
                let removedArray = splicedArray.splice(0, size);
                outputArray = [...outputArray, removedArray];
            }
        }
    }
    return outputArray;
};
```

