While below solution doesn't score very well on LeetCode in memory category (it's too verbose and takes more space to store), in a work environment, this is the preferred way to write code.
```
var chunk = function(array, size) {
    return array.reduce((accumulator, element, index) => {
        const newChunk = index % size === 0;
        const chunkIndex = Math.floor(index / size);

        if (newChunk) accumulator.push([]);
        accumulator[chunkIndex].push(element);

        return accumulator;
    }, []);
};
```
Compiler is smart enough to spit out a minified version of the function at least like this (usually it also removes the spaces). 

```
var chunk = function(arr, size) {
    return arr.reduce((a, e, i) => {
        if (i % size === 0) a.push([]);
        a[Math.floor(i / size)].push(e);
        return a;
    }, []);
};
```
We don't write code for machines. For machines, either version works the same, but for humans, first version is way easier to read and understand or to remember what it does when you come back to it after a while.

