# Intuition
I found this question very misleading.
I found the solution rather quickly , but the 'throw new Error' part was causing the console to show an error, because type ToBeOrNotToBe is typed to always return a boolean, not an error

# Approach
In order to bypass the console error, I had to add an additional testWrapper function to deal with the error throwing.


# Code
```
type ToBeOrNotToBe = {
    toBe: (val: any) => boolean;
    notToBe: (val: any) => boolean;
};

function expect(val: any): ToBeOrNotToBe {
    return {
        toBe : (val2 : any) =>{
            if (val !== val2) throw new Error('Not Equal')
            else return true
        },
        notToBe : (val2 : any) =>{
            if (val === val2) throw new Error('Equal')
            else return true
        }
    }



};

function testWrapper(func: Function): { value?: boolean, error?: string } {
    try {
        return { value: func() };
    } catch (e) {
        return { error: e.message };
    }
}

testWrapper(()=> expect(5).toBe(5))
testWrapper(()=>expect(5).notToBe(5))

/*   expect(5).toBe(5); // true
  expect(5).notToBe(5); // throws "Equal" */

```

