# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The intuition was to return an object from the function. The object would have two keys: `toBe` and `notToBe`, which are lambda functions to work according to the requirement.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- The key `toBe` will have a lambda function that takes parameter `n` and compares the value of `n` with the value of `val`. If `val` is equal to `n`, then it will return `true`. Otherwise, we will throw an error using the `Error()` class constructor with the message `"Not Equal"`.
- The key `notToBe` will have a lambda function that takes parameter `n` and compares the value of `n` with the value of `val`. If `val` is not equal to `n`, then it will return `true`. Otherwise, we will throw an error using the `Error()` class constructor with the message `"Equal"`.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Since there is no loop of recursive function call, the time complexity of the function will be $$O(1)$$, i.e. constant time.
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Since we are using only constant memory, independent of the value of `val` or `n`, the resultant space complexity is also constant, i.e. $$O(1)$$.
# Code
```
/**
 * @param {string} val
 * @return {Object}
 */
var expect = function(val) {
    return {
        toBe: (n) => {
            if(n === val)
                return true;
            throw Error("Not Equal");
        },
        notToBe: (n) => {
            if(n !== val)
                return true;
            throw Error("Equal");
        }
    }
};

