# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The problem is asking for a simple testing utility that can compare values using strict equality (===) and strict inequality (!==). We need to create a function expect that takes a value and returns an object with two methods: toBe and notToBe. These methods will compare the input value with another value, returning true or throwing an error based on the comparison.


# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Create the expect Function: Define a function expect that takes a value val.
Return an Object with Methods: Inside expect, return an object with two methods:
toBe(otherVal): Compare otherVal with val using ===. Return true if they are equal, or throw an error with the message "Not Equal" if they are not.
notToBe(otherVal): Compare otherVal with val using !==. Return true if they are not equal, or throw an error with the message "Equal" if they are.
Utilize Closures: The inner functions toBe and notToBe will have access to val from their containing scope, even after expect has finished executing. This is a closure, and it allows the inner functions to "remember" the value passed to expect.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
For both the methods, the complexity is O(1)
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
    Same for the space complexity.
