# Intuition
In the case of **toBe(val)** we need to check if the values are equal and if not we should throw an error. Not the opposite which would be: checking if the values are not equal and throwing the error.


# Approach
Basically, what I mean is:

This:
```
if(x === val) return true;
throw new Error("Not Equal");
```

And not this:
```
if (x !== val) throw new Error("Not Equal");
else return true;
```

The same goes for the other function **notToBe(val)**, too.


# Full solution would be:
```
/**
 * @param {string} val
 * @return {Object}
 */
var expect = function(val) {
    return {
        toBe: (x) => {
           if(x === val) return true;
           throw new Error("Not Equal");
        },
        notToBe: (x) => {
            if(x !== val) return true;
            throw new Error("Equal");
        }
    }
};

